[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m I remember from Einstein's theory of general relativity that gravity isn't just a force like other fundamental forces. Instead of being a carrier particle like in the force mediating theories, gravity is the result of spacetime itself being curved. Matter and energy curve the fabric of spacetime, and everything, including massless particles like photons, follow those curves.
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Light has energy, and according to Einstein's famous equation E = mc¬≤, energy gives rise to mass. Even massless energy carries gravitational "charge" so to speak, and this causes it to move along curved spacetime paths. In other words, light doesn't have rest mass, but it still has energy that creates an effective gravitational mass when moving through spacetime. This intrinsic gravitational effect is what bends the path of light in gravitational fields.
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The most famous example is how light is deflected around massive objects like the Sun. That phenomenon was one of the early confirmations of general relativity. Similarly, gravitational lensing occurs when massive objects bend the spacetime fabric, causing light from distant objects to follow the curved path.
