[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Light is affected by gravity because, according to Einstein's theory of general relativity, gravity isn't merely a force acting between masses as thought in Newtonian physics. Instead, massive objects curve the fabric of [spacetime continuum], which is the stage on which all physical events occur. This curvature affects objects and light alike, causing them to follow curved paths despite light having no rest mass.
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Light possesses energy, and as shown in Einstein's famous equation E = mc¬≤, energy is equivalent to a form of mass. While this energy doesn't contribute to the usual inertial mass that allows objects to resist acceleration, it does create an "effective gravitational mass" that determines how light interacts with heavy objects. When [light passes near a massive object like a black hole or star], it follows the naturally curved geodesic path of the spacetime warped by that object's mass, resulting in phenomena like gravitational lensing or the bending of light around the [sun].
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The bending effect becomes measurable but is still a significant part of general relativity's predictions. The famous confirmation came from the [1919 solar eclipse expedition], where light from distant stars was observed to bend around the Sun's massive gravity, further verifying Einstein's theory.
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
