[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m So, essentially, each pair \( (A, B) \) gives a line through the origin with a particular slope or is the y-axis itself. My task is to count how many distinct lines we get from all possible valid pairs.
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The set of available numbers is \( \{0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 9\} \). There are six numbers in total. I'm supposed to choose two different numbers each time, one for \( A \) and one for \( B \). Since order matters in the equation (because swapping \( A \) and \( B \) would change the slope unless it results in the same line), I need to consider all ordered pairs where \( A \) and \( B \) are different.
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m First, how many ordered pairs are there in total? Since we're choosing two different numbers from six, the number of ordered pairs is the permutation of 6 things taken 2 at a time, which is \( 6 \times 5 = 30 \) pairs.
