[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Given the function \( f(x) = 2x + \ln x \), we need to find the slope of the line passing through the point \((0, -1)\) and tangent to the curve \( y = f(x) \).
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m First, we compute the derivative of \( f(x) \):
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ f'(x) = 2 + \frac{1}{x} \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The point where the tangent line touches the curve can be denoted as \((a, f(a))\). The slope of the tangent line at this point is \( f'(a) = 2 + \frac{1}{a} \).
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The equation of the tangent line at \((a, f(a))\) using point-slope form is:
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ y - f(a) = f'(a)(x - a) \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Since this tangent line passes through the point \((0, -1)\), we substitute \( x = 0 \) and \( y = -1 \) into the equation:
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ -1 - f(a) = f'(a)(-a) \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Substituting \( f(a) = 2a + \ln a \) and \( f'(a) = 2 + \frac{1}{a} \):
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ -1 - (2a + \ln a) = -a \left(2 + \frac{1}{a}\right) \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Simplifying both sides:
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ -1 - 2a - \ln a = -2a - 1 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m This simplifies to:
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ -1 - 2a - \ln a = -2a - 1 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Bringing all terms to the left side:
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ 0 - \ln a = 0 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m Solving for \( a \):
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ \ln a = 0 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ a = e^0 = 1 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The point of tangency is at \( x = 1 \). Evaluating \( f(1) \):
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ f(1) = 2 \cdot 1 + \ln 1 = 2 + 0 = 2 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The slope of the tangent line at \( x = 1 \) is:
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m \[ f'(1) = 2 + \frac{1}{1} = 3 \]
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m 
[36m(main_task pid=25448)[0m The slope of the line is \(\boxed{3}\).
